## 5. KnightWerx fork — relevant deviations

### 5.1 Attitude D term (commit `76328d9640`, 2024-09-10, Henry Won)

Adds rate-proportional damping to the outer (attitude) loop. Without this commit the outer loop is pure P + yaw-FF; with it, it's P + D + yaw-FF. The diagram for the outer loop shows the new $-D$ block fed by $\omega$ (blue line).

Files touched:

- `src/modules/mc_att_control/AttitudeControl/AttitudeControl.{cpp,hpp}` — `update()` signature changed to accept `rates`; `_derivative_gain` member added.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control.hpp` — gain plumbing.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control_main.cpp:303` — `rates` passed to `update()`.
- `src/modules/mc_att_control/mc_att_control_params.c` — `MC_ROLL_D`, `MC_PITCH_D`, `MC_YAW_D` (default 0.0).

With params at 0.0, behavior matches upstream.

### 5.2 Heading-good-for-control bypass

Near `mc_att_control_main.cpp:331`, the yaw-setpoint reset path that would fire on EKF heading-quality drops is disabled. Effect: yaw setpoints don't snap during heading resets.

### 5.3 Subtle interaction with yaw weight

`setProportionalGain()` in `AttitudeControl.cpp:51` divides yaw P by `_yaw_w` so that `MC_YAW_P` is the end-to-end effective gain regardless of `MC_YAW_WEIGHT`. The new **D gain is not rescaled** the same way. If you set `MC_YAW_D > 0` and then change `MC_YAW_WEIGHT`, the yaw P and yaw D will scale differently.

### 5.4 Rate controller — no fork divergence

`git log hotfix..origin/dev -- src/modules/mc_rate_control/ src/lib/rate_control/` returns nothing. The dormant anti-windup gate (`rate_control.cpp:92-99`) is upstream behavior.

